There was always something a bit ridiculous about FIFA banning Luis Suarez from ‘all-football-related activity’. It was a bit like a school headmaster dishing out a month’s worth of detentions to an unruly pupil and then adding: ‘And you have to go to bed early every night with no dinner’. They were out of their element; ruling beyond their area of jurisdiction.

Barcelona pay Luis Suarez’ wages if they want him clocking in at 9.30 sharp for training at their Joan Gamper training complex who is Sepp Blatter to tell them that can’t happen. What FIFA do about a player’s participation in their competitions, however, is another matter and it is no great surprise that the Court of Arbitration in Sport (CAS) have not over-ruled them on that part of the ban.

Although both Suarez and Barcelona were hoping for more, CAS has limited itself to reigning-in the game’s governing body, rather than meddle in the number of matches it felt fitted the crime.

